The '''David Rockefeller Center for Latin American Studies''' was founded in 1994 and is based at Harvard University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drclas.harvard.edu/about|title=About|website=Drclas.harvard.edu|accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref> It was endowed by [[David Rockefeller]].
It exists to "increase knowledge of the cultures, economies, histories, environment and contemporary affairs of Latin America; to foster cooperation and understanding among the peoples of the Americas; and to contribute to democracy, social progress and sustainable development throughout the hemisphere."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drclas.harvard.edu/|title=David Rockefeller Center|website=Drclas.harvard.edu|accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref>
==Publications== The center publishes a book series, some of the titles in which are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harvardpress.typepad.com/hup_publicity/2006/05/books_on_latin_.html|title=Books on Latin America from the David Rockefeller Center - Harvard University Press Blog|website=Harvardpress.typepad.com|accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref> * ''Bitter Fruit: The Story of the American Coup in Guatemala'' * ''Titu Cusi: A 16th Century Account of the Conquest'' * ''Passing Lines: Sexuality and Immigration''
